text: We’re using these findings to build new models of how the space environment interacts with the surfaces of airless bodies.
Since these processes are ubiquitous across the solar system, knowledge about the moon can be applied to a range of other bodies.
The frequent readings from LADEE revealed gas level rise as meteor streams hit the moon, with levels returning to normal after the stream.
Interplanetary grains hit the moon at speeds exceeding 21 mi/s, releasing immense heat and vaporizing soil and the meteoroids themselves.
Our new data show that meteoroid strikes cause a predictable increase in the abundance of two key elements within the lunar exosphere.
An exosphere is the thin layer of gas surrounding a small body (the moon's is one 25-trillionth the density of Earth’s atmosphere)

LADEE is currently in elliptic orbits around Earth, called phasing loops, and will continue with two more of these elliptical orbits
The spacecraft also successfully went through its first eclipse, and operated as expected.
The spacecraft is back in Fine Pointing Mode, and did not go into safe mode before or after the burn.
Flight Dynamics preliminarily reports that it was a good burn, and will confirm later in the orbit through ranging.
We have successfully completed the Perigee Maneuver (PM-1) main engine burn. #NASALADEE
The post-burn engineering assessment is that the main engine performed very well with no issues.
The @NASALADEE spacecraft completed the AM-1b maneuver yesterday. We are currently in fine pointing mode, and everything looks good.
It will be critical for our big Lunar Orbit Insertion (LOI-1 burn) on Oct. 6. Exciting!
This was an engineering test of the main Orbital Control System thruster, the big main thruster sticking out of the bottom of the spacecraft
